"type":"ImageService3","profile":"http://iiif.io/api/image/3/level0.json"}]}}]}],"annotations":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-04932/canvas/1/page/p1","type":"AnnotationPage","items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-04932/canvas/1/3a09dd98-15c9-45ab-a363-e344b3126054","type":"Annotation","motivation":"commenting","body":[{"created":"2026-06-29T19:33:46.623Z","creator":"Tallulah Stallvik","purpose":"commenting","type":"TextualBody","format":"text/html","value":"<p>The wallpaper in the dining room <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" class=\"Hyperlink SCXW90718132 BCX0\" href=\"https://filmandfurniture.com/2018/07/wondrous-wallpaper-phantom-thread/\"><u>(“Fruit”) is derived from a William Morris design from 1866</u></a> that features pomegranates, peaches, oranges, and lemons—another example of the film’s prominent food motif (#FFFind, 2018). The combination of sweet fruits (pomegranates and peaches) and sour fruits (oranges, lemons) well represents Reynolds and Alma’s dynamic: a combination of tender lover and bitter resentment. Morris was a British artist, textile designer, and poet associated with the Arts and Crafts movement.</p>"}],"target":{"type":"SpecificResource","source":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-04932/canvas/1","selector":{"type":"FragmentSelector","conformsTo":"http://www.w3.org/TR/media-frags/","value":"xywh=pixel:1142.9579025110781,29.842134416543473,384.16035819793206,1014.5564069423928"}}}]}]}]}